Try 10, 20, or 40. 20 is good almost always.

nodes.title: üëã Welcome to Flux Level 1!
widgets_values:
üëã Welcome, **Noodler**! If you came here before SDXL workflows, no worries. The tutorial covers similar topics. If you did, Flux has some unique twists, so **don‚Äôt skip** around too fast or you‚Äôll miss the good stuff.

You probably don‚Äôt know me. Max benched me in SDXL v1.5.

Now to introduce myself: I‚Äôm **Noodletron** ü§ñ, your ComfyUI tour bot and emoji enthusiast. I‚Äôll walk you through this workflow without overwhelming you or boring your GPU into hibernation.

Without further ado, **follow that noodle.** üëâ

nodes.title: Global Models
widgets_values:
Whatever models you‚Äôve got loaded and connected to those Set_MODEL nodes?
That‚Äôs what the workflow‚Äôs running with. Period.

Wanna use GGUF? Make sure it's connected to the set_MODEL nodes.

For each Global Model node you use whether fp8 or GGUF, you need to click through and make sure it‚Äôs pointing to a model you actually have. Right. Now.

If you leave it as-is and the file name doesn‚Äôt exactly match what‚Äôs in your folder, ComfyUI will spiral into an identity crisis and self-destruct out of confusion. üí• Or you'll just get an error. ü§∑

üîç So go through Global Models and hook up FP8 or GGUF. Then click each one and select the model you have.

nodes.title: ü´ô Choose Your Sauce
widgets_values:
üçú Above is where you choose Flux Dev or Flux Schnell.
Same noodle, different sauce.

Flux Dev (quality) is tastier, but you‚Äôll be waiting 45 minutes for the chef to plate it üçΩÔ∏è.
Flux Schnell (speed) isn‚Äôt as rich, but that chef moves fast. ‚è©

Disable your previous group and enable this one. It's how we control what ComfyUI runs when we hit "Run".
